				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$F:2^X\rightarrow {\mathbb {R}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M106"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>F</mml:mi><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mn>2</mml:mn><mml:mi>X</mml:mi></mml:msup><mml:mo stretchy="false">&#x02192;</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq53.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> of an optimization problem (<italic>X</italic>,&#x000a0;<italic>f</italic>) is<disp-formula id="Equ1"><label>1</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M107">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} F(X'):=\min _{x\in X'} f(x) \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M108" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>F</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:msup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:munder><mml:mo movablelimits="true">min</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02208;</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:msup></mml:mrow></mml:munder><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_Equ1.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>for all <inline-formula id="IEq54"><alternatives><tex-math id="M109">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$X'\subseteq X$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M110"><mml:mrow><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:msup><mml:mo>&#x02286;</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq54.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. We use the convention <inline-formula id="IEq55"><alternatives><tex-math id="M111">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$F(\emptyset )=\infty $$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M112"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>F</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">&#x02205;</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>&#x0221e;</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq55.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p><p>We say that a subset <inline-formula id="IEq56"><alternatives><tex-math id="M113">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$X'\subseteq X$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M114"><mml:mrow><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:msup><mml:mo>&#x02286;</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq56.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is <italic>good</italic> if <inline-formula id="IEq57"><alternatives><tex-math id="M115">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$F(X')=F(X)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M116"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>F</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:msup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>F</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq57.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, i.e., if <inline-formula id="IEq58"><alternatives><tex-math id="M117">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$X'$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M118"><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq58.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> contains a global optimum, and <italic>bad</italic> if <inline-formula id="IEq59"><alternatives><tex-math id="M119">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$F(X')&#x0003e;F(X)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M120"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>F</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:msup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>&#x0003e;</mml:mo><mml:mi>F</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq59.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. The oracle function is by definition monotonic in the following sense:<disp-formula id="Equ2"><label>2</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M121">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} X'' \subseteq X' \Longrightarrow F(X'')\ge F(X') \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M122" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo>&#x02286;</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:msup><mml:mo stretchy="false">&#x027f9;</mml:mo><mml:mi>F</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>&#x02265;</mml:mo><mml:mi>F</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02032;</mml:mo></mml:msup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_Equ2.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>We call <italic>F</italic> an oracle function because in general there is no efficient algorithm for computing it. In fact, if we had an efficient way to compute <italic>F</italic>, we would already have solved the original optimization problem as well. Nevertheless, it is a useful theoretical construct, as we shall see below. First, it guides our construction of encodings of the original optimization problem that have the potential of being easily solved, or at least easier to solve. Second, it provides an inroad for constructing practical heuristics <italic>provided</italic> we can come up with a good approximation for <italic>F</italic>.</p><p>We start by formalizing the idea of an encoding of a landscape.</p></sec><sec id="FPar2"><title>Definition 2</title><p id="Par25">A function <inline-formula id="IEq60"><alternatives><tex-math id="M123">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
