				\begin{document}$$G=(V,E)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M830"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>V</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq408.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, a matching is a subset <inline-formula id="IEq409"><alternatives><tex-math id="M831">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$M \subseteq E$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M832"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02286;</mml:mo><mml:mi>E</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq409.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> of pairwise disjoint edges, i.e., (<italic>V</italic>,&#x000a0;<italic>M</italic>) is a graph with a maximum degree of at most 1. Denoting by <italic>X</italic> the set of matchings on <italic>G</italic>, the maximum matching problem (MMP) (<italic>X</italic>,&#x000a0;<italic>f</italic>) has the cost function <italic>f</italic> giving the number of unmatched nodes<disp-formula id="Equ7"><label>7</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M833">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} f(M) = \big |V \setminus \bigcup _{e \in M} e\big | \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M834" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mo maxsize="1.2em" minsize="1.2em" stretchy="true">|</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mi>V</mml:mi><mml:mo lspace="0.15em" rspace="0.15em" stretchy="false">\</mml:mo><mml:munder><mml:mo>&#x022c3;</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02208;</mml:mo><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:munder><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo maxsize="1.2em" minsize="1.2em" stretchy="true">|</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_Equ7.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>in a matching <italic>M</italic>. Thus, the MMP asks for a subset of edges that cover as many nodes as possible without having any node contained in more than one edge (Lov&#x000e1;sz and Plummer <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR20">1986</xref>).</p><p id="Par72">Now consider an edge subset <inline-formula id="IEq410"><alternatives><tex-math id="M835">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$S \subseteq E$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M836"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>S</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02286;</mml:mo><mml:mi>E</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_451_Article_IEq410.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. In the present context, we call <italic>S</italic> sparse if the graph (<italic>V</italic>,&#x000a0;<italic>S</italic>) has maximum degree 2, so each connected component of (<italic>V</italic>,&#x000a0;<italic>S</italic>) is a cycle or path (including isolated nodes as trivial paths). Denote by <italic>Y</italic> the set of all sparse subsets of <italic>E</italic>. Since a matching <italic>M</italic> is also a sparse subset of <italic>G</italic>, we have <inline-formula id="IEq411"><alternatives><tex-math id="M837">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
